'''''Daigo''''' ({{CJKV|j=大悟}}), also known in English translation as '''''Great Realization''''', is a book of the [[Shōbōgenzō]] by the 13th century [[Sōtō]] [[Zen]] monk [[Eihei Dōgen]]. The book appears tenth in the 75 fascicle version of the [[Shōbōgenzō]], and it is ordered 26th in the later chronological 95 fascicle "''Honzan'' edition".<ref name=textual>{{citation|last=Heine|first=Steven|title=Dōgen: Textual and Historical Studies|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2012|pages=27, 39|isbn=978-0-19-975447-2}}</ref> It was presented to his students in the first month of 1242 at [[Kōshōhōrin-ji]], the first monastery established by Dōgen, located in [[Kyoto]]. According to [[Gudō Wafu Nishijima|Gudō Nishijima]], a modern Zen priest, the "great realization" to which Dōgen refers is not an intellectual idea, but rather a "concrete realization of facts in reality"  or "realization in real life".<ref name=Gudo>{{Citation| last1 =Nishijima|first1=Gudo|last2=Cross|first2=Chodo|authorlink1=Gudo Nishijima|year = 2008|title = Master Dogen's Shōbōgenzō|volume=2|pages=103-113|publisher=Numata Center for Buddhist Translation and Research|isbn=978-1-886439-36-8}}</ref> [[Shohaku Okumura]], another modern-day Zen teacher, writes that Dōgen equates the term ''daigo'' with the network of interdependence in which all beings in the universe exist rather than something that we lack and need to obtain. Given this, Okumura writes that Dōgen is encouraging us to, "to realize great realization within this great realization, moment by moment; or perhaps it is better to say that great realization realizes great realization through our practice."<ref>{{Citation|last1=Okumura|first1=Shohaku|authorlink1=Shohaku Okumura|title=Realizing Genjokoan: The Key to Dogen's Shobogenzo|publisher=[[Foundation for the Preservation of the Mahayana Tradition|Wisdom Publications]]|year=2010|page=40|isbn=9780861716012}}</ref>

