{{Infobox person | pre-nominals = [[The Reverend]] | name = Oliver Chase Quick | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1885|06|21|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Sedbergh]], England | death_date = {{death date and age|1944|01|21|1885|06|21|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Longborough]], England | residence = | nationality = | alma_mater = | occupation = | years_active = | era = | known_for = | notable_works = <!-- produces label "Notable work"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label "Notable credit(s)"; or by |works=, which produces label "Works"; or by |label_name=, which produces label "Label(s)" --> | spouse = Frances Winifred Pearson | parents = {{unbulleted list | [[Robert Hebert Quick]] | Bertha Parr}} | awards = | module = {{Infobox clergy|child=yes | religion = [[Christianity]] ([[Anglicanism|Anglican]]) | church = [[Church of England]] | ordained = {{unbulleted list | 1911 (deacon) |1912 (priest)}} }} | module2 = {{Infobox academic|child=yes | alma_mater = [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]] | discipline = {{hlist | [[Theology]] | [[philosophy]]}} | workplaces = {{unbulleted list | [[Durham University]] | [[University of Oxford]]}} }} }} '''Oliver Chase Quick''' (21 June 1885 – 21 January 1944) was an English theologian, philosopher, and Anglican priest.{{sfnm |1a1=MacKinnon |1y=1993 |1p=101 |2a1=Robbins |2y=2008 |2p=168}}
==Early life and education== Oliver Quick was born on 21 June 1885 in [[Sedbergh]], [[Yorkshire]], the son of the educationist [[Robert Hebert Quick]] and Bertha Parr.{{sfnm |1a1=Chapman |1y=2004 |2a1=Lindgren |2y=2004 |3a1=Sell |3y=2010 |3p=143}} He was educated at [[Harrow School]] and studied classics and theology at [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]].{{sfnm |1a1=Chapman |1y=2004 |2a1=Lucas |2y=1993 |2p=4}}
Quick married Frances Winifred Pearson,{{sfn|Sell|2010|p=144}} a niece of [[Karl Pearson]].
==Ecclesiastical and academic career== Quick was ordained {{citation needed span |date=November 2017 |text=to the diaconate}} in 1911{{sfnm |1a1=Chapman |1y=2004 |2a1=Chapman |2y=2006 |2p=830}} and to the priesthood in 1912.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Prior to becoming chaplain to the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] in 1915, he was a vice-principal of [[Leeds Clergy School]] and then a curate at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], [[London]].{{sfn|Chapman|2006|p=830}} He was given his first [[incumbent (ecclesiastical)|incumbency]] in 1918 in his appointment to the vicarage of [[Kenley]], [[Surrey]].{{sfn|Chapman|2006|p=830}} He went on to be appointed to residentiary canonries of [[Newcastle Cathedral|Newcastle]] (1920), [[Carlisle Cathedral|Carlisle]] (1923), and [[St Paul's Cathedral|St Paul's]] (1930).{{sfn|Chapman|2006|p=830}} He became a professor of theology at [[Durham University]] in 1934 and was appointed to a canonry of [[Durham Cathedral]] ''ex officio''.{{sfn|Chapman|2006|p=830}} He moved to [[Oxford]] in 1939, having been appointed to the [[Regius Professor of Divinity|Regius Professorship of Divinity]] at the [[University of Oxford]], which carried with it a canonry of [[Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford|Christ Church Cathedral]].{{sfnm |1a1=Chapman |1y=2006 |1p=830 |2a1=Lucas |2y=1993 |2p=17 |3a1=Sell |3y=2010 |3p=144}} He remained in the post until his death in 1944.{{sfn|Chapman|2017|p=39}}
In his works he advocated the doctrines of [[soul sleep]] and [[conditional immortality]].{{sfn|Quick|1938|pp=260–261}} He was one of the leading exponents of orthodox Anglicanism{{sfnm |1a1=Chapman |1y=2006 |1pp=830–831 |2a1=Mozley |2y=1945 |2p=36}} and upheld a position similar to that of the authors of ''Essays Catholic and Critical'' (1926). He followed systematic and synthetic rather than historical methods and expressed his thought in a modern way.
Quick died on 21 January 1944 in [[Longborough]], [[Gloucestershire]], and was buried four days later in the churchyard in Longborough.{{sfn|Sell|2010|p=147}}
