{{Other people|William Knight}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Use British English|date=July 2017}}
'''William Angus Knight''' (1836–1916) was a British writer, born at [[Mordington]], [[Scotland]], and educated at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. From 1876 to 1902 he was [[professor]] of moral philosophy in the [[University of St Andrews|University of St. Andrews]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=KNIGHT, William Angus|magazine=Who's Who|year=1907|volume= 59|page=999|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yEcuAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA999}}</ref> In the field of philosophy his work, editorial and other, includes his collection of ''Philosophical Classics for English Readers'' (15 volumes, 1880–90), some of which he wrote. Although he wrote numerous publications, he is probably best known for his works on [[William Wordsworth|Wordsworth]]. His edition of ''Wordsworth's Works and Life'' (1881–89) is contained in 11 volumes. He presented to the [[trustee]]s of [[Dove Cottage]], Grasmere, the poet's former home, all the editions of Wordsworth's poems which he possessed. He also corresponded with [[Robert Browning]] about [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning]], and on his retirement in 1905 he came to [[Florence]]'s Swiss-owned so-called [[English Cemetery, Florence|English Cemetery]] to plant the red rose at her tomb, which still flourishes, to honour women's learning, though the enamelled plaque celebrating that act has since been stolen. His portrait was presented to [[St Andrews University]] by the [[Ladies Literate in Arts]] whose admission he encouraged.
==Works== * ''[https://archive.org/details/humeknight00kniguoft Hume]'' (1886) * ''[https://archive.org/details/principalshairph00kniguoft Principal Shairp and his Friends] (1888) * ''Essays in Philosophy, Old and New'' (1890) * ''The Philosophy of the Beautiful'' (two volumes, 1891–93) * ''The Christian Ethic'' (1894) * ''[https://archive.org/details/aspectsoftheism00knig Aspects of Theism]'' (1894) * ''[https://archive.org/details/cu31924014138386 The Transactions of the Wordsworth Society]'' (1880–86) * ''Selections from Wordsworth'' (1889) * ''[https://archive.org/details/wordsworthianase00knigiala Wordsworthiana]'' (1889) * ''Through the Wordsworth Country'' (1892) * ''Wordsworth's Prose'' (1893) * ''[https://archive.org/details/englishlakedistr00kniguoft The English Lake District, as Interpreted in the Poems of Wordsworth]'' (1878–91) * ''[https://archive.org/details/cu31924065010989 The Poetical Works of William Wordsworth]'' (1896) * ''The Works of William Wordsworth and Dorothy Wordsworth'' (twelve volumes, 1896–97) * ''Dove Cottage from 1800 to 1900'' (1900) * ''[https://archive.org/details/cu31924029079668 Lord Monboddo and Some of his Contemporaries]'' (1900) * ''Inter Amicos'' (1901) * ''[https://archive.org/details/propatriaetregin00knig Pro Patria et Regina]'' (1901) * ''[https://archive.org/details/variastudiesonpr00knigiala Varia: Studies on Problems of Philosophy and Ethics]'' (1901) * ''[https://archive.org/details/retrospects00kniguoft Retrospects]'' (1903) * ''[https://archive.org/details/poetsonchristmas00knig The Poets on Christmas]'' (1906) * ''Things New and Old'' (1909) * ''The Golden Wisdom of the [[Apocrypha]]'' (1910) * ''[https://archive.org/details/glamourofoxfordd00knigiala The Glamour of University of Oxford]'' (1911) * ''[https://archive.org/details/robertbrowningce00knig The Browning Centenary]'' (1912) * ''An Eastern [[Anthology]]'' (1912) * ''[https://archive.org/details/cu31924105501914 Coleridge and Wordsworth in the West Country: Their Friendship, Work, and Surroundings]'' (1914)
