{{Infobox person | name = William Craig | image = WilliamCraig1977.jpg | alt = William Craig, UC Berkeley Logic Group picnic 1977. | caption = William Craig, UC Berkeley Logic Group picnic 1977. | occupation = Philosopher | birth_date = {{birth date|1918|11|13}} | birth_place = [[Nuremberg]], [[German Empire]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2016|01|13|1918|11|13}} | death_place = [[Berkeley, California]], U.S. }}
'''William Craig''' (November 13, 1918<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Dictionary of Modern American Philosophers|author1=Shook, J.R.|author2=Hull, R.T.|date=2005|volume=1|publisher=Thoemmes Continuum|isbn=9781843710370|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ijpj1tB3Qr0C|page=548|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref> – January 13, 2016) was an American academic and philosopher, who taught at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California]]. His research interests included [[mathematical logic]], and the [[philosophy of science]],<ref>{{cite web|title=William Craig|url=http://philosophy.berkeley.edu/news/detail/64|publisher=University of Berkeley|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref> and he is best known for the [[Craig interpolation]] theorem.
==Biography== William Craig was born in [[Nuremberg]], [[German Empire]], on November 13, 1918. He graduated from [[Harvard University]] with a [[Ph.D]] in 1951. He married Julia Rebecca Dwight Wilson and had four children: Ruth, Walter, Sarah, and Deborah. In 1959 he moved to UC Berkeley. He died on January 13, 2016, at the age of 97.
==Achievements==
Craig is particularly remembered in two theorems that bear his name: * the [[Craig interpolation]] theorem, and * [[Craig's theorem]], also known as ''Craig's axiomatization theorem'' or ''Craig's reaxiomatization theorem''.
